  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 12 @ 2023/2024",
    "Question": {
      "content": "In the Faraday's experiment to determine electromagnetic induction, what is the effect of moving the bar magnet and the coil simultaneously?",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "Galvanometer deflection is maximum",
        "Galvanometer deflects in the opposite direction",
        "Galvanometer deflects in the same direction",
        "Galvanometer does not deflect"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "Galvanometer does not deflect"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<p>In Faraday's experiment, electromagnetic induction occurs when there is a relative motion between the magnet and the coil, changing the magnetic flux. If both are moved simultaneously at the same speed and direction, the relative motion is zero, so no change in flux occurs, and the galvanometer does not deflect.</p>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Faraday's Law of Induction",
